s guide to freshwater fishes and was reading the information about distribution of pike earlier today. It said they're present in the Great Lakes states, but largely absent from Lower Michigan and Indiana. I know you have talked about pike, Rick, I just wonder if the information in the book is accurate. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfishtalkandfishingreports.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bigbass101>Bigbass101</A></span><br> Posts: 970<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(2/15/04 11:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffishtalkandfishingreportsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=217.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pike in Indiana?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but largely absent from Lower Michigan and Indiana<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Couldn't be further from the truth Marty.  Our lakes are loaded with them.  I would say that within a 75 mile radius on the Michigan and Indiana state line, there is roughly 95 % of the lakes that have Pike in them.  To put it in perspective, that's probably 190 out of 200 lakes!  So to answer your question.  Yes there are some discrepancies in the write up for sure.  Thanks for asking.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :thumpup --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/posticons/pi_thumbsup.gif ALT=":thumpup"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><a href="http://www.geocities.com/rdvtavssvjnm/BASS/BASSx.html">
