Speaking of Tippecanoe, I remember an article I read about fishing this river (open water) in Jan or Feb with large chubs for BIG pike.  The area around the junction of St Rd 4 and the river was mentioned and these guys fished anywhere there was a confluence of a creek or drainage ditch.  That article is about 15 yrs old but should still work..<br>
Jack <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfishtalkandfishingreports.showUserPublicProfile?gid=martyfromny>MartyFromNY</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 305<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(2/17/04 8:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffishtalkandfishingreportsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=217.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pike in Ind</span><hr size=1> The book I bought is Ken Schultz's &quot;Field Guide to Freshwater Fish.&quot; It's a brand new book, but...the information is taken from his &quot;Fishing Encyclopedia&quot;, so who knows how old it might be.<br>
<br>
